2022 OUT!! WHAT A YEAR…

Ok, tbh, I think it’s safe to say the bar was set quite low by 2021 and especially by its predecessor (the year who shall not be named)…That said, it was incredible to travel the globe again, to play for live audiences again of so many sizes, hear different languages again and experience different cultures. 

I’m incredibly lucky to be able to participate in so many different different musical/social spaces, and grateful to everyone for welcoming me and understanding that there are those of us are too restless and creatively curious to “stay in our lane” (this is how I envisioned things years ago when I was “burrowing down” or whatever and refocusing from being an easily pigeonholed player). Also thankful to all the musicians I got to make music with this year, whether giant festivals or hip clubs in the Village (rip #55Bar which sadly closed its doors). 

Anyway…. This year great friends were made, important new musical relationships were forged and no sign of letting up next year. Here’s a quick live gig highlight reel which barely scratches the surface but seems to segue together somehow. 

Have a happy, safe New Years and may all your hopes for the 2023 come true. 🙌🎸🥂

I’m back…I needed a few days to collect thoughts on Jeff Beck. I never got to meet the man, just a seriously appreciative listener, but his sudden departure on Wednesday really hit home (I can only imagine what friends of mine who knew and worked with him are going through). 

So I ended up putting aside whatever else I was doing and fell into an unplanned, all day/late into the evening for several days hibernation, with a laptop, plenty of coffee and lots of Jeff Beck music.

I’ve seen plenty of moving tributes, well crafted obituaries and excellent articles. Yet I felt like more needed to be said. While I did include a few personal anecdotes - discovering his work, hearing him live once - that’s not the main focus. If there is a main focus, it’s that it may be time to rethink this whole G.O.A.T thing (obviously, I nominate @jeffbeckofficial). 

Now, I could’ve easily written 10k words or more. In fact I had close to that before whittling it down. The result is a @newyorkermag length piece, so set aside 15 min or so if you have it. 

Either way, feel free to swipe for a few text samples along some very kind initial feedback (pun not intended) from my “testing grounds (Twitter). 

LINK IN BIO, as they say, and if you’ve subscribed to my @substackinc page, it’s already in your inbox. 🙏🏼👍🎸

Crushing news. In a parallel w last week’s devastating loss for music, David Crosby was continuing to create work that reflected an evolution, didn’t sound dated or repetitive and amazingly, stood up to his earlier material, which includes some of the most important and influential sounds of our times. From The Byrds, to Crosby Stills, Nash & Young (and just CSN) to producing the debut of Joni Mitchell (an album which I’m convinced influenced the later folk side of Led Zeppelin, who were still mainly heavy blues rock at the time) to his current Lighthouse Band and so much in between, his impact on music as we know it is immeasurable. 

Online, he could be quite snarky (and fittingly was a fan/collaborator of @snarkypuppy ), rubbed some the wrong way (including his old Byrds & CSNY mates, some of whom still weren’t speaking to him) but always meant well (however clumsily). He was good-hearted, had uncompromising integrity & was unflinchingly honest (some might say: to a fault). I never met him in person but did have quite a few mutual music friends who are in my thoughts (along with his family), I know they’re devastated. I did have some fun interactions with him online, was proud to defend him, which became a minor headline (Google our names together). 

Yes, he’d become an octogenarian - quite incredible considering what he’d put himself through (especially for someone without that rare “Keith Richards” constitution) - and had had some recent health scares but still…he always seemed to pull through and it looked like he’d continue to defy the odds. 

So far 2023 is feeling like 2016 as far as these things go (make it stop, please). 

Peaceful Journey, Croz ☮️🙏🏼😢

Ps See “Remember My Name” (the brilliant DC doc if you haven’t )

NEW EPISODE ALERT:  It was heart-wrenching, yet highly informative (and also humorous, as JB would likely have it), to pay tribute to the great one on the this special episode of my podcast @moodsandmodes. As a bonus, I was joined by Vernon Reid, Carmine Appice, Melissa Dragich (JB’s longtime PR rep) & Dave Rubin (author of JB method books), who all weighed in. Link in bio or listen wherever you get your podcasts. 

“Over a remarkable 50-year career, Jeff Beck’s style of guitar playing reshaped the world of music. One of the essential guitarists of the British Invasion, Beck possessed a mercurial, lyrical style that sounded equally at home in thunderous blues-rock and soft-focus fusion. He played both styles in his long career, channeling psychedelia, heavy metal, and jazz-rock as he did so. 

In this episode, Alex pays tribute to the late, great guitarist with a few special guests. Vernon Reid joins to talk about the impact that Beck had on the world of music, including his work with Stevie Wonder and the complicated story behind the song Superstition. Carmine Appice shares stories from their days in Beck, Bogert, and Appice, the legendary supergroup they formed in the early 70’s, and explains his decision to pass on being part of Jeff’s ‘Blow by Blow’ album and tour in order to join Rod Stewart’s band. Beck’s longtime publicist Melissa Dragich joins the conversation and reminisces about a missed opportunity between Beck and Prince, and music journalist Dave Rubin describes that one time he saw Beck put BB King on notice.

Yet another of the all-time greatest has left the planet/building. 

Like Jeff Beck, @wayneshorterofficial never stopped evolving as a musician. He was redefining modern jazz in the early ‘60s as a leader and with Art Blakey, in the late ‘60s with Miles Davis (arguably Miles’ greatest band w @herbiehancock @roncarterbassist & #tonywilliams), defining jazz-rock in ‘70s is with the mighty #WeatherReport (w Zawinul, Jaco P & too many to name) and maintaining his high standards ever since. In some ways, he was an inverse of JB because Jeff’s Beck’s strength was as an instrumentalist, whose essential tunes were mainly composed by others (Stevie Wonder, Jan Hammer, Max Middleton, Mingus, Page etc). Wayne, meanwhile, had his biggest strength as a composer (not to take anything away from his playing - well worth transcribing!). 

While advanced improvisational music often runs the risk of going over the heads of non-insiders, Wayne’s compositions are highlighted by melodies as memorable as any pop tune, defying the complexities of the chord changes underneath. His tunes somehow manage to be incredibly listenable while avoiding common chord movements. 

There are too many great examples to name but this album, “Juju” is an early favorite and a great place to start, especially the title track. Follow with “Speak No Evil” and, work your way through his work with Miles, Weather Report and his work across the decades. Farewell #WayneShorter RIP 🎷

It’s been said often enough but bears repeating that this week has been an especially brutal one in terms of musical losses. From sax/composition giant Wayne Shorter to multi-instrumentalist David Lindley to Nashville recording/touring bassist Michael Rhodes and now #garyrossington (all on the heals of a tough year so far that has included the losses of Jeff Beck and David Crosby). 

Although Lynyrd Skynyrd gets overshadowed by cultural/political issues (from “Sweet Home Alabama” in the ‘70s to “Red, White & Blue” in 2003 - 20 yrs ago already!), there’s no denying the band - and the guitarists in particular - have always played their asses off.  From the original triple tag-team (my favorite was Steve Gaines, RiP) to more recent lineups (including my friend @officialdamonjohnson), the guitar lineup has always been unassailable. That become even more clear after seing them live in the mid 90s (with @teslaband) and more recently sharing the bill on a few Euro-fests. 

All along, through triumph and tragedy (see 1977 plane crash) it’s been held down by Rossington who, in the mold of Dickey Betts, Leslie West and others, played without fancy gadgets or tricks, opting to create musical statements with the pure tone of a high quality Gibson through an amp (a “simple kind of man,” indeed). 

Just the other night, after playing a show (one in which I admittedly used a lot of gadgets), I was saying hello to a group of fans afterwards. The venue PA was broadcasting a local classic rock station and all of a sudden, “That Smell” came on. It kicks off with Rossington’s lead line with smooth bends & vibrato drenched in fiery feedback. “Stop!” I said. “Listen to that.” We all paid a moment of silence in tribute (completely unaware of the news the next day would bring) only resuming conversation as the feedback faded and the song continued in the background. Now it all seems serendipitous. #ripgaryrossington

It’s the 100th(!) birthday of Wes Montgomery. There’s little to say about Wes that hasn’t been said. If jazz guitar has a “Jimi Hendrix” - which is not a sonic comparison, of course, but rather meant to imply a similarly dominant, towering, preeminent figure and prime influence upon later generations - he’s probably it. I was tempted to play a bit in tribute but being just back from tour, am a bit knackered, as they say overseas (scroll back a couple posts to hear some playing with a bit of Wes’ influence). Instead, here’s a quick story: 

This album was recorded in my hometown, Berkeley, Ca, years before I was born. I always felt a special connection to it and the guitar on the front. In the mid-90s, I came across a similar blonde Gibson L5, from 1976 (his was from 1960). I made a deal with myself to get my jazz guitar side to a pro level, no matter how many years/decades it took. Otherwise, the L5 would go back (good incentive -I still have it, pic 2)

Now…it takes nothing away from my own blonde L5 or the inspiration it provides to find that Wes never actually owned his! 

A fine blog: “Dutchbopper’s Jazz Guitar Blog”, describes an encounter with what he thought was the guitar, but wasn’t sure. Then it was confirmed. Soonafter, a French Guitar Mag did a “Rare Bird” profile on it. Some of it is translated below (roughly) Scroll for pics. The French mag cleverly figured out that in every pic with that guitar, Wes is wearing the same outfit. Thus it was a borrowed guitar used for a photo-shoot that yielded several promo pics and album covers!

From the French translation: “And how can you be so sure that this is the same instrument?" dear friend, we have two clues that allow us to authenticate it without a doubt. First, on the inlay of the headstock a small motif is missing, to the right of the amphora. Or rather, it is not missing, it is under the varnish which has not been removed on that spot. Secondly, the veins of the pickguard, like the fingerprints of the thug, do not deceive: we rarely meet identical patterns. This is what allows us to say that you have before you the model held in the prestigious hands of Wes Montgomery. 

Happy 100th 🎂 #wesmontgomery

Incredibly sad to learn of the passing of #ryuichisakamoto. Not just a favorite Japanese composer but a favorite composer period. I was especially taken in by one of his most recent works, the theme from “Minamata.” As far as the film, I admit it was the cool cameras in the movie poster that first got my attention, held by some unrecognizable actor playing a photographer. This turned out to be #JohnnyDepp, who - whatever you think about his recent tabloid attention - is fantastic in “Minamata” (his best role in years) and deserves props for helping bringing this important unappreciated story of a true environmental disaster to life. A more current event, the pandemic, caused the film to be sidelined and though finally released, ultimately fly under the radar. However, everyone should see it and Sakamoto’s score is as essential as William’s themes are to Spielberg films. During the pandemic, my version of learning to break bread was upping my piano playing, and while I don’t claim to be at pro studio/performance level (I’d still hire someone else at this point), Sakamoto’s main “Minamata” - on a lone piano - grabbed me right away and was at a tempo/technique level that actually seemed manageable.  it has opened up much in the way of composition and emotion, so I offer a quick sample as a humble tribute (swipe to view/hear). RIP to a master.

Dear Friends: 

 A few days ago, I sent a late night “family emergency” email to the band. The hour was 3am. I was at my mother’s hospital bedside, in a tiny chair, still in stage clothes, a soft guitar case crammed in the corner (I’d come straight from my gig downtown, taking over from someone very dear who’s been beyond invaluable). Thankfully, things have improved somewhat, knock on wood, and my mom’s out of the Emergency Room, in more comfortable surroundings at the hospital, with release in the (hopefully) not too distant future.  It’s a good thing I happened to be home during such a turbulent week. 

At the same time, it’s become very clear how many urgent matters need hands-on attention by yours truly, in light of all this. All of which to is to say that, unfortunately, there is no way to avoid Testament’s upcoming European tour being affected.

At least there is protocol for these situations. At this point, Testament has done an untold number of tours with bands in which one or more band members have had to be filled in for, most often for family issues (which become more frequent for everyone as life goes on). And having assessed this situation, it seems to make the most sense - assuming things continue in a present positive direction - for me to sit out part of this current tour and rejoin approximately mid-way. While I hate to miss/cancel shows (and never have, as far as I can remember), family first, as they say.  CONTINUED IN COMMENTS

There are debates about “natural talent” vs “hard work” but rare is the craftsman who is not only topped off with the highest levels of prodigious talent but also happens to have an “early to rise,” maximum-productivity work ethic that rivals any Fortune 500 CEO. Every Pat Metheny album and tour is a whole new show, band & level (my 5th PM gig). 

As attested to by others on the tour, Pat’s high standards are contagious, elevating all to reach their higher levels, from the youth-defying virtuosos Chris Fishman and Joe Dyson ( I can’t remember hearing folks this young play like THAT!) to the crew. And the tour manager John and Priscilla both with earlier roots in the heavy music side of things. Although we’d spoken before - PM did my @moodsandmodes  podcast - it was beyond great to meet in person as well as get a closeup glimpse of the rig (which includes a @kemperamps_official identical to mine, had NO idea!). Also great to reconnect w @andy.pitcher from @daddarioandco following an exclusive hang a few months back.  All at the élèvent and legendary, Beacon, with an interior that feels like time travel. Back in January, when Peter was the grand finale of our lineup at @joesatriani’s G4 experience, that was quite memorable. Joe’s band, Kenny, Bryan, Rai, nailed the tunes with just an afternoon to rehearse and the performance was first rate. 

Yet great as that was, PF’s touring band (sorry I don’t have everyone’s IG), dialed in from weeks on the road, top shelf concert sound, lighting and gear - early generation amps pedals (Marshalls, Mutrons & more), a festival of bursts and 335s and of course, the one and only “Phoenix” - and everyone pushing themselves to new heights night after night? That’s a whole other experience. 

The “Never Say Never” tour was so named because Peter’s recent and rare physical ailment, Inclusion-Body Myositis, marked 2022 as his final year of touring. But just as the long missing Phoenix Les Paul reappeared unexpectedly, so has PF’s energy, to the point where he found himself up for another go and hinted it may not be the last after all (perhaps “Never Say Never Again” with nods to James Bond?) 

It was like being transported to a time I was too young to attend the great concerts of the era - the mid 1970s.  And as great as the hits were, the covers (from standards to Soundgarden) and Humble Pie segment were worth the price of admission alone, along with a sample of brand new original music which held its own (not easy in a set list like that!). 

  Our mutual friend, drum legend Anton Fig, was in attendance too (first pic). Big thanks to my local pal and video wiz, director Adam Dubin (last pic) for instigating a road trip to Port Chester (us big-city folk can be a bit insulated…guilty as charged). Also thanks to the super hospitable crue including a couple good tech buds I’ve had some crazy road adventures with.. the mighty @jimmyjamesb & @terrythedrake 

Beyond worth the trip and a night we’ll be talking about for years to come. If the Frampton band 2023 comes around near you, make the extra effort. You won’t be disappointed. You will be shown the way. 🔥

It doesn’t matter how many times you’ve heard #metallica songs (as most of us have for decades now)- this new show is a fresh, new experience; a work of art. At this point, these guys could just be relaxing, enjoying the (very) good life but instead they’ve become one of the hardest working acts, period. Trust me, you’ve never experienced a concert like this. 

Watching from the floor, sometimes they’re super close, like a club show. Then, there they are half-way across the NFL field. Then they’re back (or just one or two guys). Yet anywhere you watch, it hits just as hard, thanks to the “water tower” big screens and unreal lights. It says a lot that on the first “no repeat weekend” show - a set that included, “Creeping Death,” “Orion,” “Seek & Destroy,” “Fade to Black,” Master of you-know-what and so much more, it felt nothing was missing, despite no “For Whom the Bell Tolls,” “One” “Enter Sandman” (all no doubt saved for Sunday).

Other observations: @panteraofficial totally works as a stadium band.  @wolfvanhalen crushing it on the bill, supporting this band that once supported VH on a stadium tour, back when they were the “new kids,” is a beautiful example of “full circle.” 

About the pics: In the spirit of “Sir, you’re no Jack Kennedy,” I’m no @rosshalfin. But for just an iPhone (14pro), it’s not bad, if I may say (next time someone’s getting hit for a photo pass so I can bring one of my Leicas).

There are very few acts that are genuine giants these days. The symbolism of this venue being the home of @nygiants (and of course, MetLife) is not lost. 

Thanks to these guys for keeping it going, moving it forward and inspiring all of us. I’m sure I don’t need to tell most of my followers (many of whom I imagine already have tix) but when they come around…don’t miss! 🔥

It is difficult to put into words the level of intensity experienced last night: Proof that high emotion and peak technical facility are not mutually exclusive. @shakti50tour is a show that those of us who were there will be reminiscing about for many years to come.

In the early 70s, when Maestro John McLaughlin stepped out from his position in Miles Davis’s pioneering, “Bitches Brew” era lineup (+ a noteworthy association w Tony Williams), he launched what some of us might think of as one of the “Big Four” of jazz-rock bands, along with Chick Corea’s Return to Forever, Wayne Shorter & Joe Zawinul’s Weather Report and Herbie Hancock’s Headhunters (ALL alumni of King Miles! @milesdavis)

At the peak of #mahavishnuorchestra’s popularity, they sold untold albums, sold out The Fillmore on both coasts and even supported giants like The Who. But realizing the hugeness was interfering with the artistry, JM launched his next project that - save for the virtuosity - couldn’t have been more different: Shakti with master tabla player #zakirhussain. One can only imagine the faces of label CEOs & promoters hoping to replicate Mahavishnu’s crossover appeal as they saw John seated on the floor barefoot & in traditional garb, side by side with some of India’s top masters - no drum kit, no electric bass, no keyboard.

That was 50 (!) years ago. The lineup may have changed (it now includes Maestros Shankar Mahadeven on vocals, Ganesh Rajagopalen on violin & Selvaganesh Vinayakram on hand drums, along with ZH & JM), but no step has been lost - all the more remarkable when you consider JM turned 81 (!) this year. I was put in a trance & yanked out of it all evening, not contemplating the process behind the music (which is refreshing for a change). Yes, musicians appreciate this stuff, but the civilians loved it too.

Had a bomb detonated the venue, a seizable percentage of NYC’s  guitar community would be wiped out (sorry for the morbid thought)

Pics by yours truly  Video borrowed from jazz journalist legend @billmilkowski (more centered than us). Last pic from a few yrs back.This won’t happen often and may not again. As musicians, it is a duty to witness #shakti50 if you can! 🔥

Happy 48th! I don’t have time to post about most album anniversaries (even my own!) but special mention here. 

It might come as a surprise that I’ve become a big listener of Brian Eno in recent years. After decades of playing professionally, my instinct is to seek out listening material that offers a cleansing from typical patterns of harmony and melody. This recording captures that perfectly with help from virtuoso guests like Robert Fripp on guitar, Phil Collins on drums/percussion and Percy Jones on fretless bass, (whom I’ve had the honor of working with lately in the project PAKT, which is a huge thrill - a new LP has just been released, we’ll be at @cuttingroomnyc Nov 26 and have an extensive tour across the US in Jan/Feb 2024) 

“Another Green World” predates Eno’s production of pop artists (little bands like U2, Talking Heads etc oh, yes David Bowie), as well as seminal ambient work (ie “Music for Airports”). It is a perfect precursor to both, with plenty of ambience along with some pop moments that are equally unpredictable. 

This disc is also an early example of Eno applying the concept of “Oblique Strategies,” a series of short phrases and instructions designed to nurture the creative process. I bought a set of his cards (avail on @brianeno website and there are online versions as well) and found them useful. Some of the advice might feel abstract at first but if given a chance, can trigger new thought patterns and help get out of artistic ruts, being stuck on a project etc (examples: “Go outside,  shut the door” or “Look closely at the most embarrassing details. Amplify them”)

“I feel uptight on a Saturday Night” 

No shortage of Kiss tribute posts today, this Saturday Night of their last show (for real, it seems). Also, no shortage of recent pics of me as Paul on Halloween (swipe for one more 📷 @carlosgunngt). 

I get asked “Why weren’t you Ace?” Three reasons -
1) Starchild makeup is easier and no silver on hand 2) Minutes to showtime 3) I should probably be one the two Jewish guys (rim shot 🥁). Fittingly, i was Paul on Halloween as a ten year old (somewhere there’s a negative or proof shoot, to be shared when it turns up), the first year I played guitar. 

Kiss gets picked a lot in the pantheon of rock bands. I’ve never heard a Kiss fan argue they’re “better” musicians than say, Led Zeppelin, Queen or Van Halen (whom Gene Simmons gets credit for nurturing early on). But the fact is they have had an effect on seemingly everyone, from Rage Against the Machine, to Rush, Lenny Kravitz, Garth Brooks, Pantera and too many artists in & out of rock music to name. 

So whatever you think about the lineup changes, drama, polarizing statements or any other Kiss Kontroversy, there’s no denying their impact. Not to make this about me but - as I’ve pointed out many times - they were the “straw that broke the camels back- as far as me picking up a guitar as a kid. 

They’re also retiring on a date that is later than Slayer, Soundgarden, Nirvana and many others who’ve come and gone since KISS’s 70s heyday. Like Ozzy, Sabbath, Motley  and even Phish, the original final show was anything but, however this time  is different. They’ll be taking the stage soon (wish I was there) so I’ll sign off by paraphrasing another iconic band:  For those about to rock (for the last time), we salute you. 🥂🎸🔥🔥🔥🔥
I’ve had backstage practice sessions interrupted by ice coolers, fire alarms & more (see earlier videos). As you can see, practicing at home has its own hazards 🤷‍♂️ 🐈

Back in my early 20’s, I had pretty good chops & technique for my age (before the internet era of kids playing VH at age two - which is only a slight exaggeration) but knew I needed work on dynamics, harmonic vocabulary, diversity etc  When this guy (whom I’d seen bring down the house with his bass on the Satriani tour a few years earlier) needed a guitar player, I figured it was probably a long shot. But the prep of learning the songs, a blend of high level instrumental rock, jazz/rock, prog, funk & more featuring 6-string guests with such names as Johnson, Holdsworth & Satch, would be a veritable boot camp of musical self-improvement. So why not go for it full throttle. Lo & behold, I got hired (what the heck?!), experienced artistic growth beyond imagination and made a great lifelong friend in the process! 

Despite this history & despite reuniting for numerous tours & gigs since the mid 2010s, our first recording together finally came out THIS YEAR (Check out “Hold Fast”). If in So Cal, hear us live during NAMM - Friday Jan 26. And whatever you do, don’t miss my chat on the new episode of @moodsandmodes my pal and yours: Stuuuuuuuuu!

McCoy Tyner’s solo on “Softly as in a Morning Sunrise” (a chorus & a half, as far as I could get). 

One of my fav solos of his, from “John Coltrane Live at the Village Vanguard. This take is more like a piano trio tune (John C only joins in w soprano sax on the back half)

In honor of the late great McCoy’s bday (Dec 11, 1938) which was a week ago today but A) I was in flight and B) transcribing this stuff ain’t easy (took longer than planned). 

 Notes: 

* I love this solo for many reasons but especially for the fact that it goes so many unpredictable places on a tune that - as far as standards go - is considered basic (“Softly” is mostly a vamp on Cm7) Obviously, the playing is far from basic

* Piano parts don’t always migrate easily to guitar, so you do the best you can. There are a couple sudden octave jumps. Some of the super-fast runs just had to be approximated 

*  Listening backs there are a few more of his left hand “comp” chords that I probably could’ve grabbed (and I can think of a few player friends who’d have gotten them), but not bad, if I may say 

* Learning piano parts like this on gtr, even just a tiny bit, is very useful for getting out of the usual “guitar patterns” Try it and have fun! 

Gear- Guitar: Gibson 347, late ‘80s, Amp: vintage 1966 Fender blackface Deluxe Reverb (This is one of those times when a digital amp modeler, no matter how good, just won’t do)

Santa came earlier this year, and brought a couple wonderful gifts that work great together. I’m a little late demoing this unique instrument that truly blends acoustic and electric qualities  @powerselectricguitars (in association with @taylorguitars ). It’s running through a Quad Quartex by @neuraldsp. Sound-patch is a simple factory preset (called “Airy Reverbs”) and I didn’t have to tweak much. Thinking about doing more solo melodies like this, post-holidays.  Thank you “Santas”(you know who you are). 

Ok, I’m not exactly Mr Holiday Spirit (although my resume includes an association with a well known Christmas concert tour For that matter. my culturally designated holiday already took place 🕎). But this melody has always struck a chord, pun not intended. And it’s naturally what came out while just messing around with this combination of gear, an “instant arrangement”

About the song: According to legend (and Wikipedia) “…on Christmas Eve 1818, (Father Joseph) Mohr brought the words to musician Franz Xaver Gruber and asked him to compose a melody and guitar accompaniment for that night’s mass, after river flooding had possibly damaged the church organ.” I’ll bet they never imagined one day, guitars would be capable of tones that have majestic qualities like an organ. 

On a slightly more serious note “Silent Night” is a song written during the aftermath of the Napoleonic Wars and seems especially fitting during these times. I’m sure some would rather I don’t reference current events, others will take offense for not speaking out more or not taking the position they expect. But I’m also sure most agree, we can all use a moment of silence and reflection, less talking/judgement more listening. Time for a Silent Night, indeed. 

  Merry Christmas Eve to all observing, Seasons Greetings to everyone and true hopes for peace on Earth

NEW EPISODE ALERT! 

A tradition that happens early each year is the Super Bowl. So what better way to kick off the New Year than a “Super Bowl” of podcast episodes?? 

Obviously, I don’t need to say much about these three giants (not NY Giants - although two are from Long Island) but here’s a chance to better know the minds behind some of most groundbreaking guitar excursions of modern times. Behind the wild string bends, screaming feedback and manic facial expressions are three gentlemen - philosophical, funny and just a pure pleasure to shoot the breeze with and gain insight from.

Topics include the birth of the G3 in the mid-90s - an era in which the culture had recently (and strangely, imo) turned against guitar virtuosity - finding your own voice on your instrument, learning from other players without sounding like them, modern vs vintage gear, perfectionism vs acceptance, the age of phone cameras & social media vs the pre-internet era & much more. 

Thanks @joesatriani @stevevaihimself & @officialericjohnson for the incredible hang and all they do. If you can, don’t miss the G3 Reunion on tour (the OG G3). Tix at g3tour.com
